    {
      "id": "readonly-queue-review",
      "title": "Read-only review identifies two behavioral defects",
      "category": "review",
      "passed": true,
      "score": 10,
      "maxScore": 10,
      "latencyMs": 9526,
      "terminal": "completed",
      "reply": "Two concrete defects in `queue.mjs`:\n\n**1. `drain` processes one too many jobs and can invoke `handle` on `undefined`**\n- Function: `drain`\n- Bug: The loop uses `index <= Math.min(limit, queue.length)` instead of `index < ...`.\n- Consequence: If `queue` has 3 items and `limit` is 3, the loop runs for indices 0, 1, 2, **3**, so it calls `handle(queue[3])`, which is `undefined`. This processes an extra non-existent job. If `limit` is larger than the queue, the same `undefined` invocation occurs at `queue.length`.\n\n**2. `acknowledge` does not await the store removal**\n- Function: `acknowledge`\n- Bug: It calls `store.remove(id)` without `await` and immediately returns `{ acknowledged: true }`.\n- Consequence: If `store.remove` is async and fails (e.g., network or disk error), the caller is told the job was acknowledged even though the removal may not have completed or succeeded. This can lose work because a failed acknowledgement can go undetected and the job may be retried or left in an inconsistent state.",
